R Notes from February 2

Loading Data

Create the link for the dataset

www <- "http://staff.elena.aut.ac.nz/Paul-Cowpertwait/ts/ApprovActiv.dat"

Load the dataset into R

Build.dat <- read.table(www, header=T)

Create “Approvals” time series

Approvals <- ts(Build.dat$Approvals, 
                start=c(1996,1),
                freq=4)

Create “Activity” time series

Activity <- ts(Build.dat$Activity, 
                start=c(1996,1),
                freq=4)

Plot data

ts.plot(Approvals,Activity,
        lty=c(1,2))

lty determines the line types, change lty to c(1,3) to plot Activity with dots instead of short lines etc.

Autocovariance function (acvf) and Autocorrelation function (acf)

Compute acf for approvals

acf(Approvals)

You can also store and access the estimated autocorrelation function:

Approvals.acf <- acf(Approvals)

#Get the estimated first 10 acf's
Approvals.acf$acf[1:10]
##  [1]  1.00000000  0.80800769  0.45525857  0.13836488 -0.05717653
##  [6] -0.10930026 -0.07312348 -0.03707759 -0.04961307 -0.08744189

We next compute the first acf (lag=1) using the equations

Approvals.n <- length(Approvals)
Approvals.mean <- mean(Approvals)
Approvals.centered <- Approvals-mean(Approvals)
Approvals.autocovariance.1 <- (1/Approvals.n)*sum(Approvals.centered[-1]*Approvals.centered[-Approvals.n])
Approvals.autocovariance.0 <- (1/Approvals.n)*sum(Approvals.centered^2)
#print the acf
Approvals.autocovariance.1/Approvals.autocovariance.0
## [1] 0.8080077
#the acf value is the same as the one computed by R
Approvals.acf$acf[2]
## [1] 0.8080077

Covariance

Compute covariance

cov(Approvals,Activity)
## [1] 1882549

Compute correlation

cor(Approvals,Activity)
## [1] 0.4321844

Following is an alternative correlation computation using standard deviations:

A.A.cov <- cov(Approvals,Activity)
Approvals.sd <- sd(Approvals)
Activity.sd <- sd(Activity)
A.A.cov/(Activity.sd*Approvals.sd)
## [1] 0.4321844

Cross correlation function

ccf(Approvals,Activity)

ccf(Approvals,Activity,lag.max = 40)
